{"questionId":"27963","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Six restaurant locations (labelled <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>D</mtext></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>E</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>F</mtext></math>) are shown, together with their Voronoi&nbsp;diagram. All distances are measured in kilometres.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/acc0315b5119f8e934ef7f20a3ae6df2c39a32af.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Restaurant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math> is at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and restaurant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>D</mtext></math> is at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>)</mo></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Restaurant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math> is at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>)</mo></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the equation of the perpendicular bisector of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BC</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>midpoint&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>correct use of gradient formula&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>gradient of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BC</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>negative reciprocal of gradient&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>perpendicular gradient&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;(or&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>17</mn></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27963","referenceCode":"22N.2.SL.TZ0.3c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the equation of the perpendicular bisector of BC.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.5—Intersection of lines, equations of perpendicular bisectors"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}